<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-053-666  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 053 666.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  Jan 13 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>MCI Mail service fax restrictions.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>McCormick, John.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   MCI Communications Corp. (services).andO;Ticker:    MCIC.andO;Topic:     TelecommunicationsMCI Mail (Electronic mail system)Electronic mail systemsEvaluationFacsimile.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>MCI MAIL SERVICE FAX RESTRICTIONS ARLINGTON, VIRGINIA, U.S.A., 1990 JAN 11(NB) -- This bureau learned today that some fax machines are being connectedto 800 lines but that phone companies and fax services are not quite up tospeed yet on this service.andM;In particular, this bureau uses MCI to transmit most text facsimile messagesbut discovered that MCI Mail would not accept a certain publisher's 800number for a fax transmission.andM;MCI Mail told this bureau today that MCI fax service will work to an ATandamp;T 800number but in the Chicago area only.andP;  If an MCI 800 number is used for a faxline, MCI Mail can access that number throughout the U.S.andM;A spokesperson for MCI told this bureau that initially it could not accessany 800 fax service, but that it had added the above-described coverage areasand conditions and was endeavoring to add the ability to access 800 lines tothe MCI Mail interface.andM;Currently, attempts to enter an unacceptable 800 number for fax transmissionvia MCI Mail results in a rejection of the number.andM;MCI Mail is a simple-to-use, highly popular electronic mail service which canalso accept a client's ASCII text files for transmission to a fax terminal,greatly reducing the need for an actual fax machine and eliminating the needto have a fax line tied up while your office machine attempts to make aconnection and deliver a fax message.andM;(John McCormick/1990111)</TEXT></DOC>